---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import BarChart from '../../../components/BarChart.astro';
import KeyFigure from '../../../components/KeyFigure.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="PISA 2022: Immigrant Student Achievement Gap by Country — Official OECD Data | Immigration Factbook" lang="en" description="Official OECD PISA 2022 data on math score gaps between immigrant and native-born students across 20 countries. 83% of the raw gap is explained by socioeconomic factors, not origin.">

<main class="theme-page">
  <div class="page-header">
    <nav class="breadcrumb">
      <a href="/en/">Immigration Factbook</a> <span>›</span> <span>Compare by Theme</span>
    </nav>
    <h1>PISA 2022: Immigrant vs Native Student Performance — 20-Country Comparison</h1>
    <p class="intro">
      OECD PISA 2022 is the most comprehensive international dataset measuring academic performance gaps between students with an immigrant background and native-born students. On average across OECD countries, immigrant students score 29 points lower in mathematics than native-born peers. After controlling for socioeconomic status (ESCS index), this gap shrinks to just 5 points. <strong>83% of the raw gap is explained by socioeconomic factors — not by immigrant origin itself.</strong>
    </p>
    <p class="intro-sub">
      Definition: "Immigrant students" = at least one parent born abroad (second generation) or student born abroad (first generation). ESCS = Economic, Social and Cultural Status index combining household income, parental education, and cultural resources at home.
    </p>
    <div class="lang-switch">
      <a href="/themes/education/">🌐 日本語で見る</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="charts-section">
    <div class="key-figures-row">
      <KeyFigure value="29 pts → 5 pts" label="OECD average math gap: immigrant vs native students (raw → after socioeconomic control)" tone="accent" />
      <KeyFigure value="83%" label="Share of the gap explained by socioeconomic factors (ESCS), not immigrant origin" tone="accent" />
    </div>

    <BarChart
      title="Persistent gap after socioeconomic control (math, PISA 2022) — European countries"
      unit=" pts"
      bars={[
        { label: 'Finland', value: 42, note: 'After ESCS control: +42 pts (raw gap: +65 pts)' },
        { label: 'Sweden', value: 34, note: 'After ESCS control: +34 pts (raw gap: +63 pts)' },
        { label: 'Norway', value: 36, note: 'Raw gap: +36 pts (adjusted figure not published)' },
        { label: 'Germany', value: 32, note: 'After ESCS control: +32 pts (raw gap: +59 pts)' },
        { label: 'Denmark', value: 28, note: 'After ESCS control: +28 pts (raw gap: +54 pts)' },
        { label: 'Netherlands', value: 27, note: 'After ESCS control: +27 pts (raw gap: +58 pts)' },
        { label: 'France', value: 20, note: 'After ESCS control: ~+20 pts (raw gap: +51 pts)' },
        { label: 'Switzerland', value: 19, note: 'After ESCS control: +19 pts (raw gap: +53 pts)' },
        { label: 'Belgium', value: 17, note: 'After ESCS control: +17 pts (raw gap: >55 pts)' },
        { label: 'Portugal', value: 25, note: 'After ESCS control: +25 pts (raw gap: +32 pts)' },
        { label: 'Spain', value: 7, note: 'After ESCS control: +7 pts (raw gap: +32 pts) — ESCS explains >60% of gap' },
      ]}
      sourceLabel="OECD PISA 2022 Results Volume I — Immigrant Background and Student Performance"
      sourceUrl="https://www.oecd.org/en/publications/pisa-2022-results-volume-i_53f23881-en/full-report/immigrant-background-and-student-performance_f469d45e.html"
      sourcePrefix="Source: "
    />
    <p class="chart-note">
      Positive values = native-born students outperform immigrant students. Values shown are after ESCS socioeconomic control. Norway: adjusted figure not published; raw gap shown. Italy and Ireland: gap becomes non-significant after control (not shown).
    </p>

    <BarChart
      title="Countries where immigrant students outperform native-born peers (points-based immigration) — PISA 2022"
      unit=" pts"
      bars={[
        { label: 'Australia', value: -26, note: 'Immigrant students outperform native-born by 26 pts (after ESCS control)' },
        { label: 'New Zealand', value: -16, note: 'Immigrant students outperform native-born by 16 pts (after ESCS control)' },
        { label: 'United States', value: -16, note: 'Immigrant students outperform native-born by 16 pts (after ESCS control)' },
        { label: 'United Kingdom', value: -12, note: 'Immigrant students outperform native-born by 12 pts (after ESCS control)' },
      ]}
      sourceLabel="OECD PISA 2022 Results Volume I — Immigrant Background and Student Performance"
      sourceUrl="https://www.oecd.org/en/publications/pisa-2022-results-volume-i_53f23881-en/full-report/immigrant-background-and-student-performance_f469d45e.html"
      sourcePrefix="Source: "
    />
    <p class="chart-note">
      Negative values = immigrant students outperform native-born peers. These countries use points-based immigration systems that select for education and skills, resulting in highly educated immigrant parents whose children benefit from greater cultural capital.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="methodology-note">
    <h2>Key methodological notes</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Definition of "immigrant student"</strong>: OECD defines this as having at least one parent born abroad (second generation) or being born abroad oneself (first generation). National statistics may use different definitions (citizenship, foreign-born, etc.).</li>
      <li><strong>ESCS index</strong>: Economic, Social and Cultural Status — a composite of household wealth, parental education, and cultural resources (e.g., books at home). Controlling for ESCS isolates the effect of immigrant background from poverty.</li>
      <li><strong>Points-based immigration effect</strong>: Australia, New Zealand, Canada, and the UK select immigrants based on education, skills, and language ability. Their immigrant populations have above-average education levels, and their children inherit greater academic capital.</li>
      <li><strong>Language environment</strong>: In the 8 European countries with large persistent gaps, 60–85% of immigrant students speak a language other than the host country's at home. This is a major driver of the gap that remains after ESCS control.</li>
      <li><strong>First vs second generation</strong>: Data from Norway, Italy, and Denmark show that second-generation immigrants (born in the host country) have substantially smaller gaps — convergence across generations is the norm.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="table-section">
    <h2>PISA 2022 Math Gap: Country-by-Country Data</h2>
    <div class="table-wrapper">
      <table class="comparison-table">
